message.content:
The only non-terminal that can produce the terminal symbol t1 is

    NT91 → 't1'

NT91 appears on the right–hand side of only one binary rule in the entire grammar:

    NT118 → NT91 NT120

So whenever t1 is generated, it is the first symbol produced by NT91, and at least one further symbol must follow, generated by NT120 (since NT120 cannot be ε in a Chomsky-normal-form grammar).

In the string we are checking, t1 is the very last token.  
Because a symbol t1 generated by NT91 must always be followed by something produced by NT120, the grammar can never generate a string that ends with t1.

Hence the given string cannot be derived from the start symbol S.

No

The start symbol S expands only as

S → NT146 NT9.

Whatever string the grammar generates must therefore begin with a token produced by NT146.

The only productions for NT146 are  
NT146 → NT188 NT169  
NT146 → 't57'  
NT146 → 't46'.

So the first token can be

• t57 (from the second or from NT188 → 't57'),  
• t46, or  
• one produced by NT188 via NT37:

 NT188 → NT37 NT84  
  NT37 → 't10' | 't2' | 't40'  
  NT37 → NT89 NT180, with NT89 → 't76' | 't27'.

Hence the first token that any sentence in the language can have is one of  
t57, t46, t10, t2, t40, t76, or t27.

The string provided starts with t47.

Since t47 is not among the possible first tokens, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT146 NT9  

so the very first terminal of any generated string must come from NT146.

The only ways to derive terminals from NT146 are  

• NT146 → 't57'  
• NT146 → 't46'  
• NT146 → NT188 NT169  

The first two rules clearly yield either t57 or t46 as the first token, never t26.

For the third rule the first token comes from NT188.  
NT188 can produce

 – NT188 → 't57' (first token t57)  
 – NT188 → NT37 NT84 (first token produced by NT37)

NT37, in turn, can give

 – NT37 → 't2', 't40', or 't10' (first token t2 / t40 / t10)  
 – NT37 → NT89 NT180 (first token produced by NT89)

NT89 yields

 – NT89 → 't76' or 't27' (first token t76 / t27)  
 – NT89 → NT146 NT15 (first token again determined by NT146)

Thus every possible first terminal obtainable from NT146 is confined to the set  
{t57, t46, t2, t40, t10, t76, t27}.  
The terminal t26 never appears in this set.

Because the given string begins with t26, it cannot be generated by NT146, and therefore cannot be generated by S.

Hence the grammar does not produce the provided string.

No

The start symbol is

S → NT146 NT9

NT146 can generate either one token (‘t57’ or ‘t46’) or two tokens (NT188 NT169 → ‘t57’ followed by one of ‘t45 / t19 / t35’).  
Because the second token of the string is ‘t57’, NT146 can only supply the first token (‘t57’).  
Therefore NT9 must generate the remaining 24 tokens:

t57 t47 t54 t7 t28 t39 t32 t54 t4 t29 t53 t57 t72 t72 t54 t29 t20 t14 t67 t68 t19 t52 t36 t38

NT9 has exactly one rule:

NT9 → NT58 NT157

Hence these 24 tokens must be split into
   • some prefix produced by NT58 and  
   • the rest produced by NT157.

1.  Structure of NT157  
   NT157 → ‘t34’                               (length 1)  
   NT157 → NT8 NT119                     (length = length(NT8)+1)

   NT119 always yields exactly one token (‘t38’).  
   NT8 is either
        – ‘t47’                           (length 1)  
        – NT55 NT152            (length 2 or 3, because NT55 is ≤2 tokens; NT152 is 1)

   Consequently NT157 can generate only 1, 2, 3 or 4 tokens, and its last token must be ‘t38’.

   So NT58 must account for the other 20-23 tokens.

2.  Structure of NT58  
   NT58 → ‘t77’ | ‘t64’                                (length 1)  
   NT58 → NT51 NT156                              (length = length(NT51)+1)  
   NT58 → NT21 NT163                              (length = length(NT21)+1, but NT163 is always ‘t69’)

   Neither ‘t77’, ‘t64’ nor ‘t69’ appears in the 24-token suffix, so only the rule
        NT58 → NT51 NT156
   can be used.  NT156 is a single terminal chosen from {t2, t3, t16, t22, t53}.  
   The only such token present in the suffix is ‘t53’, occurring 11 tokens from the start of the suffix.

   Therefore NT58 necessarily ends with that ‘t53’, i.e. NT58 generates exactly the first 11 tokens
        t57 t47 t54 t7 t28 t39 t32 t54 t4 t29 t53
   while NT157 would have to generate the remaining 13 tokens
        t57 t72 t72 t54 t29 t20 t14 t67 t68 t19 t52 t36 t38.

3.  But, as shown in step 1, NT157 cannot be longer than 4 tokens, so it is impossible for NT157 to cover 13 tokens.

Since no other splitting is possible (the position of the unique ‘t53’ fixes NT58’s length), the required derivation cannot exist.  Hence the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is 

S → NT146 NT9  
      NT9 → NT58 NT157  

The final two tokens of the string are “t47 t38”.  
NT157 can produce either ‘t34’ or NT8 NT119, and NT8 → ‘t47’, NT119 → ‘t38’.  
Hence NT157 must be NT8 NT119 and it consumes the last two
tokens.

That leaves the first 32 tokens to be generated by NT146 NT58.

1. NT146 can produce either  
   a) ‘t46’ (a single token), or  
   b) NT188 NT169 (at least two tokens, and the first of them is never ‘t46’).

Because the very first token of the string is ‘t46’, NT146 has to use
alternative (a) and contributes exactly the first token.

So NT58 must generate the 31-token substring

t44 t57 t57 t47 t54 t7 t28 t22 t1 t13 t63 t4 t7 t72 t54
t67 t12 t16 t47 t39 t29 t20 t14 t45 t54 t62 t71 t19 t68 t78 t69

2. NT58 has only four possibilities:

   NT58 → ‘t77’      (one token)  
   NT58 → ‘t64’      (one token)  
   NT58 → ‘t16’      (one token)  
   NT58 → NT51 NT156 (≥2 tokens)  
   NT58 → NT21 NT163 (≥2 tokens)

The last token of the required substring is ‘t69’.  
Only the rule NT58 → NT21 NT163 can place ‘t69’ at the end,
because NT163 → ‘t69’ and no other right–hand side of NT58 contains ‘t69’.

Thus we must have NT58 → NT21 NT163 with

NT21 generating the first 30 tokens  
NT163 generating the final ‘t69’.

3. NT21 can be ‘t72’ or NT130 NT85.  
In our substring the first token is ‘t44’, so we need NT130 → ‘t44’
followed by NT85 generating 29 tokens.

4. NT85 → NT184 NT104 and NT104 → ‘t78’.  
Therefore NT184 must produce the 28-token sequence that *ends*
with ‘t68’ (the token immediately before ‘t78’).

5. NT184 → NT55 NT118 and NT118 can be just ‘t68’.  
Hence NT55 would have to generate the remaining 27-token prefix  

t57 t57 t47 t54 t7 t28 t22 t1 t13 t63 t4 t7 t72 t54
t67 t12 t16 t47 t39 t29 t20 t14 t45 t54 t62 t71 t19

6. But NT55 has only the following forms:

   NT55 → ‘t75’ | ‘t63’ | ‘t22’                        (1 token)  
   NT55 → NT70 NT36                                    (2 tokens)  
   NT55 → NT161 NT164                                 (≥2 tokens)

   • NT70 NT36 can yield only two tokens, never 27.  
   • The terminal alternatives obviously cannot.  
   • In NT161 NT164, NT161 produces one terminal (‘t57’ or ‘t39’);
     NT164 begins with either ‘t32’, ‘t72’, ‘t47’, ‘t76’ or ‘t28’.
     None of these possibilities matches the second token ‘t57’ of the
     required 27-token sequence, so the 27-token substring cannot come
     from NT161 NT164.

Therefore NT55 cannot produce the needed 27-token block, so NT184
cannot produce its 28-token block, so NT85 cannot supply the 29 tokens,
so NT58 cannot deliver the 31-token substring, and consequently S
cannot generate the given 34-token string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
